<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is the debt snowball method?", answer: "The debt snowball method pays off debts from smallest balance to largest, regardless of interest rate. After paying minimums on all debts, extra money goes to the smallest balance first. Once that debt is paid off, its payment rolls into the next smallest. This method provides quick psychological wins that help maintain motivation." },
  { question: "What is the debt avalanche method?", answer: "The debt avalanche method pays off debts from highest interest rate to lowest. After paying minimums on all debts, extra money goes to the debt with the highest rate. This method minimizes total interest paid and is mathematically optimal, saving you the most money over time." },
  { question: "Which is better: snowball or avalanche?", answer: "The avalanche method saves more money in interest, while the snowball method provides faster psychological wins. If staying motivated is your challenge, snowball may work better. If minimizing cost is your priority, avalanche is the better choice. The best method is the one you will stick with." },
  { question: "How much extra should I pay toward debt?", answer: "Even an extra $50-100 per month can significantly accelerate debt payoff. The more extra you can pay, the more interest you save and the faster you become debt-free. Review your budget for areas to cut and redirect those savings to debt repayment." },
  { question: "Can I combine snowball and avalanche methods?", answer: "Yes, some people use a hybrid approach. They start with the snowball method to eliminate a few small debts for motivation, then switch to the avalanche method for the remaining larger debts to minimize interest. The key is to stay consistent with extra payments." }
]) %>

